MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Phase 9 lever 0b. Wave 2 DOSBox-X smoke after lever 1 (patches 0009-0011
+ nx 0045) showed a visible-rendering regression: title scene painted only
into a 320×240 box in the upper-left of a 640×480 framebuffer, leaving the
rest as garbage. SDLDBG.LOG sequence (build/stage/SDLDBG.LOG):

  mode-set #1 (entry): requested id=0x0136 320x240 16bpp (prev id=0xFFFFFFFF)
  mode-set #1 (exit ok)
  mode-set #2 (no-op): mode_id matches current, returning true
  [lifecycle] CreateWindowFramebuffer #1 (exit fast): vram_w=320 vram_h=240
  [lifecycle] GetWindowSurface: new surface=6dcd30 (320x240)
  mode-set #3 (entry): requested id=0x0111 640x480 16bpp (prev id=0x136)
  mode-set #3 (exit ok)
  [lifecycle] UpdateWindowFramebuffer: lazy-reinit ok=1 ... fb_size=614400
                                       vram_w=640 vram_h=480

So the SDL3-DOS backend correctly picked the closest match for the app's
SDL_CreateWindow(320, 240, FULLSCREEN) at mode-set #1, the renderer was
created against the 320×240 surface, and then SDL3 fired mode-set #3 to
640×480 — which lever 1's lazy-fb_state-init helpfully extended fb_state
to 640×480 dimensions, but the renderer still has its 320×240 backbuffer
and writes only the upper-left corner into VRAM.

Root cause
----------

SDL3's window/fullscreen reconciliation in SDL_video.c paths through
SDL_UpdateFullscreenMode → SDL_GetWindowFullscreenMode →
SDL_SetDisplayModeForDisplay. When SDL_GetWindowFullscreenMode finds no
explicit mode set on the window AND the window has SDL_WINDOW_FULLSCREEN,
it falls back to the display's desktop mode. DOSVESA_VideoInit hard-codes
desktop_mode to whatever's closest to 640×480 (SDL_dosvideo.c:169) — even
on a card with native 320×240 modes available. The fallback fires from
ApplyWindowFlags → SDL_SetWindowFullscreen during SDL_FinishWindowCreation,
which is what produces mode-set #3 in our trace.

This is the SDL3 framework's documented behaviour, not a bug per se — but
on the SDL3-DOS backend specifically, mode-set #3 is destructive: it
changes VRAM dimensions out from under a renderer that has no event-loop
integration to react to PIXEL_SIZE_CHANGED with a backbuffer rebuild.

Fix
---

New hint SDL_HINT_DOS_PIN_WINDOW_TO_NATIVE_MODE. When set, the SDL3-DOS
backend's DOSVESA_SetDisplayMode rejects any subsequent mode-set request
whose dimensions differ from the active mode (rather than going ahead and
breaking the renderer's geometry). Suppression is by-dimension; the
existing same-mode-id no-op early return handles the same-dimensions
case. Suppressed calls return true (claiming success) so SDL3's window
setup machinery keeps believing fullscreen worked — we just don't do the
hardware mode change.

The gate logs through doskutsu_dbg_log so the suppression appears in
sdldbg.log alongside the mode-set traces from patches 0008/0009. Look
for "mode-set #N (suppressed by PIN_WINDOW_TO_NATIVE_MODE hint)".

Targets and non-targets
-----------------------

Designed for cards that natively expose the app's requested mode (e.g.
Cirrus + UNIVBE has 320×240 at modes 0x01D9 / 0x01F8 / etc, per the
gateway4 wave-1 UNIVBE capture). On Mach64 + M64VBE (no 320-wide modes
because the Mach64-CT chip lacks line-doubling), mode-set #1 is ALREADY
the 640×480 fallback, so this hint becomes a no-op — confirmed by the
build/stage SDLDBG.LOG dump which shows mode-set #1 picking 0x0111 on
the M64 path. No regression risk on the Mach64 target.

A separate future patch will address the Mach64 stretch case (no native
320×240 mode) — out of scope for lever 0b.

Local-only patch per workspace policy (memory note "SDL upstream —
local patches only"): never PR'd upstream, sidestepping
vendor/SDL/CLAUDE.md's no-AI-PRs restriction. Documented in the new
hint's doxygen block.

Why DOS needs this
------------------

DOS-only fix in the DOS backend's mode-set chokepoint. No effect on
non-DOS builds (the hint is a string never read by other backends).
Layered on patches 0009 (mode-set lifecycle trace), 0010 (PREFER_LFB),
and 0011 (lazy fb_state re-init); the trace from 0009 is what made
mode-set #3 visible enough to write this fix against.

